Data Structures

c()

The function c() combines or concatenates its arguments into a vector (a 1-dimensional data structure consisting of 1 or more elements).

  • All of the elements must be of the same type.
  • I cant combine character and numeric types in the same call to c()

Heres two examples using numeric and character data types:

## Create a vector of numbers:
num_vec  = c(1, 4, 8, 9, 13)

## Create a vector of characters:
char_vec = c("a", "fish", "data is cool")

## Typing the name of the vector into the console prints the contents
num_vec
## [1]  1  4  8  9 13
## The print() function accomplishes the same task:
print(char_vec)
## [1] "a"            "fish"         "data is cool"

Length ()

  • x - an R object. For replacement, a vector or factor.
  • value - a nn-negative integer or double (which will be rounded down).
## Calculating the size of my vector

length(num_vec)
## [1] 5

matrix ()

  • creates a matrix from the given set of values.
vector1 = c(2,4,6,8,10,12)
matrix(data = 6, nrow = 3, ncol = 3)
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    6    6    6
## [2,]    6    6    6
## [3,]    6    6    6

data.frame()

  • couples variables which share similar properties of lists and matrices
a = c(2)
b = c(4)
c = c(6)
df = data.frame(a,b,c)
  • Ginkgo Data
nrow(ginkgo)
## [1] 756
ncol(ginkgo)
## [1] 6
dim(ginkgo)
## [1] 756   6
